[5] USA (SC): brain surgery alert
Date: Wed 1 Aug 2012
Source: Fox 29 News, South Carolina [summ., edited]
http://www.wflx.com/story/19164044/11-upstate-brain-surgery-patients-at-risk-for-fatal-disease


Eleven Upstate brain surgery patients were put at risk for acquiring a fatal brain disease that affects only one in a million. The Greenville Hospital System (GHS) said they've told patients who were operated on in February [2012] that the same tools used for their surgeries were used on a patient doctors later found had Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, or CJD. In a statement, GHS said they always clean their tools according to US standards, but they didn't use the additional CJD sterilization because they hadn't known until later that one of their patients had it.

The release said they have since told each of the 11 who had surgeries in February, who may have been exposed. One of the patients has been a nursing home, barely able to communicate. Her husband says he's nervous, because he has no idea how anyone would know if his wife got the disease through surgery. He spoke with doctors on 13 Jul 2012 and then received a letter describing what they had discussed in brief. "Please know that the Greenville Hospital System stands ready to provide her with all reasonable and appropriate treatment, at no cost to you, if she is diagnosed by biopsy with Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease," the letter read. The victim's husband said he's still not heard back from the hospital and doesn't know much of what is going on, aside from what he researched online. "Already I'm worried about what happened the 1st time, and now they throw this on top," he said.

CJD is like a very fast-acting dementia. It causes the brain to shut down, which eventually leads to a body shutdown. The National Institutes of Health, NIH, said it happens most often in people over 65. NIH said it's caused by an abnormal protein and usually [occurs] sporadically. Sometimes it's genetic, and fewer than one percent of cases are acquired, like this would be, if someone gets it. That concept of rare possibility is what GHS stressed in its letter to the husband.

In GHS's release, Dr Thomas Diller, vice president of quality and patient safety, said, "This is a very unusual event. After a full assessment and discussion with the CDC, we believe the risk of transmission of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease to any patient is extremely small." Biopsies and autopsies are the only way to know for sure if someone has it, but there may be symptoms everything from a change in the way someone walks to confusion, hallucinations, muscle stiffness or twitching, and sleepiness.

[Byline: Dana Wachter]

