[6] UK (Northern Ireland): vCJD incidence
Date: Mon 16 Jul 2012
Source: Londonderry Sentinel [edited]
http://www.londonderrysentinel.co.uk/news/local/six-mad-cow-deaths-1-4036219


The human variant of 'mad cow disease' was mentioned on 6 Northern Ireland death certificates over the past 3 years, the Finance Minister Sammy Wilson has revealed. The Minister provided details of the number of deaths registered in Northern Ireland between 2009 and 2011, where 'Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease' was mentioned on the death certificate.

Mr Wilson's colleague the Health Minister Edwin Poots said that of 176 deaths from [variant] Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease across the UK since 1995, just 3 had occurred in Northern Ireland. Mr Poots said none of the 3 deaths were due to blood transfusions and that it was impossible to say for sure if the 3 local deaths were due to the consumption of infected beef products.

"None of the 3 deaths in Northern Ireland was associated with blood transfusions. While there is good, although indirect, evidence that variant CJD originated from transmission of infection from bovine spongiform encephalopathy in cattle to humans via infectivity in food, the source of infection in 3 cases in Northern Ireland is not known," he added.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Only 3 of the 176 confirmed case of vCJD recorded in the United Kingdom (population 62 million approximately) occurred in Northern Ireland (population 1.8 million approximately).

In contrast, in the Republic of Ireland (population 4.6 million approximately) there has been a total of 4 cases, whereas there have now been 27 cases (2 surviving) in France (population (65 million). - Mod.CP]

